		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/30/arts/television/30NARCOS/30NARCOS-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/30/arts/television/30NARCOS/30NARCOS-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/30/arts/television/30NARCOS/30NARCOS-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003882390" width="592" height="330" alt="Gabriela de la Garza in &quot;Narcos&quot;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="330"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Gabriela de la Garza in "Narcos"</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Netflix</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/narcos-episode-7-recap-diana-kidnapping/" data-title="&#8216;Narcos&#8217; Episode 7 Recap: The Trouble With Steve Murphy" data-description="The show&#039;s main American character is one of its weaknesses.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/category/television/tv-recaps/narcos/">Read all of our &#8220;Narcos&#8221; recaps</a>.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Season 1, Episode 7: &#8220;You Will Cry Tears of Blood&#8221;</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs time to talk about Steve Murphy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The real Steve Murphy did indeed play a significant role in the hunt for Pablo Escobar &#8212; spoiler alert: he was the first American on the scene when the hunt finally ended &#8212; and the real Steve Murphy and the real Javier PeÃ±a also acted as consultants on âNarcos.â Nevertheless, the character Steve Murphy has a much more expansive role on the show than any one person could plausibly have in real life. Heâs the Zelig of âNarcos,â present whenever an American is needed in high-level discussions with the Colombian government or on ride-alongs with the Search Bloc or whenever the writers need to tie up some dangling narrative thread. Even though heâs based on one person, Murphy has the feel of a composite character, like several American agents compressed into one for the purpose of storytelling economy. Docudramas like âNarcosâ should be granted that kind of flexibility (indeed, the disclaimer that opens every episode allows for it) but it hasnât always served Murphy the character well and the seventh episode is a good example of that. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-362373"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Murphy plays two distinct roles on the show. The most important (and most effective) is his role as the narrator, our entrÃ© into the morally and politically complicated world of Colombian drug trafficking and the protracted hunt for Escobar. For as dominant a voice as Murphy has been in âNarcos,â the writers have been wise not to cast him as a âwhite saviorâ type whoâs there to bring clarity and justice to a narco-state under siege. This is a Colombian fight, and Americans like Murphy are supporting players. In fact, having him one stop removed from the action is largely what makes him so sensible as a narrator: Guys like Carrillo or Gaviria or certainly Escobar himself are too immersed in their specific roles to comment on the larger picture. Murphy is our eye in the sky. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Heâs also our boots on the ground, occasionally, and thatâs where âNarcosâ has gotten into a little trouble. The first episode used the club shootout that killed Poison as an example of the imperfect and often unsavory nature of pursuing justice in Escobarâs Colombia, and the hunt for a prostitute/informant in the next episode gets into uglier territory still. At the time, Murphy chided PeÃ±a for shielding him from his extra-legal tactics, but the show has since backed off the idea that Murphy could be pulled into the muck. The righteousness of his methods have never come into question; more often, the show has put Murphy close to the center of the action when he doesnât plausibly belong there. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Consider this sequence from Episode 7: In the fallout over Avianca Flight 203, Escobar wants anyone who can connect him to the bombing dead, including the wife of the poor sap who unwittingly carried the explosive onto the plane. So as Poison and his partner hunt her down, Murphy and PeÃ±a happen to be combing the same neighborhood to find narcos who can lead them to Escobar. Having the D.E.A. agents stumble across the sicarios at the very moment Poison is about to cap an infant is an absurd coincidence and the shootout that follows isnât any more convincing. For PeÃ±a to be thwarted by a pistol-wielding child makes for forced commentary on Escobarâs recruitment of the young, but thatâs nothing compared to Poison clicking an empty chamber when he has a gun pointed at Murphyâs head. Thatâs the type of thing that happens in TV shows. âNarcosâ is shooting for a higher standard. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The episode, and the show over all, is on more solid footing when it steps back and considers the larger forces at play. The plane bombing affirms Escobarâs status as a narco-terrorist and at first he doesnât shrink from the label, continuing a war against the Colombian government thatâs ostensibly about extradition, but seems more a manifestation of inchoate rage. âYouâre the one who says the politicians donât give a shit about the public,â Gustavo reminds him, putting the lie to the populist rhetoric of Escobarâs own political campaign. Meanwhile, the newly elected Gaviria has answered Escobarâs domestic terror with equal aggression against the MedellÃ­n cartel. When Escobar changes strategy and starts kidnapping family members of the countryâs political elite, he finally applies the right kind of pressure on Gaviria. His monstrousness is purposeful again. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The kidnapping of Diana Turbay, the daughter of a former Colombian president and a highly respected broadcast journalist, is seen here as a turning point in Gaviriaâs approach to the war, too. Escobar succeeds in putting Gaviria in an awkward spot; her father Julio CÃ©sar Tublay, having advised Gaviria to âtrust his instinctsâ during the inauguration, is now prepared to drop all financial and political support if the new president doesnât takes steps to bring his daughter back safely. But itâs an opportunity for Gaviria to change tactics, too, and quietly escalate the hunt for Escobar while ânegotiatingâ with him. The two adversaries have each other boxed into positions that make them both uncomfortable, and will be a stiff test of their cleverness and moxie. And if âNarcosâ stays true to form, itâll almost certainly be more compelling than Murphy and PeÃ±a trading bullets with a couple of goons. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Parting shots</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8226; Fascinating exchange between Escobarâs wife and mother about the Avianca bombing. Mother: âYou think he did it? Surely not. Blow up that plane?â Wife: âOf course he did it, Hermilda. But he had his reasons.â Itâs been suggested before that Hermilda was in denial about the source of her sonâs riches. Her denial is formidable, but it isnât total. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8226; One other big development this episode: The tension between the MedellÃ­n cartel and the Cali cartel. This will come into play more later, but Escobarâs capture owes much to the disturbing fact that rivals were angling for a piece of his business. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8226; Suggesting that Turbay was kidnapped at Valeria Valezâs request is the type of bold dramatic license that not using Virginia Vallejoâs real name makes possible.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8226; Itâs safe to say that baby wouldnât have testified in court. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/narcos-episode-8-recap-gustavo-dead/">Read our Episode 8 recap here</a>.</em></p>
	</div>
